[h1]The text-decoration Property [/h1]

The text-decoration property specifies how the text will be decorated. 

Commonly used values are:
[b]none[/b] - The default value, this defines a normal text
[b]inherit[/b] - Inherits this property from its parent element
[b]overline[/b] - Draws a horizontal line above the text
[b]underline[/b] - Draws a horizontal line below the text
[b]line-through[/b] - draws a horizontal line through the text (substitutes the HTML [b]<s>[/b] tag)

The example below demonstrates the difference between each value. 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="none">This is default style of the text (none).</p>
<p class="inherit">This text inherits the decoration of the parent.</p>
<p class="overline">This is overlined text.</p>
<p class="underline">This is underlined text.</p>
<p class="line-through">This is lined-through text.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="525"]p.none {
   text-decoration: [b]none[/b];
}
p.inherit {
   text-decoration: [b]inherit[/b];
}
p.overline {
   text-decoration: [b]overline[/b];
}
p.underline {
   text-decoration: [b]underline[/b];
}
p.line-through {
   text-decoration: [b]line-through[/b];
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2601" width="100%"]
[note]You can combine the [b]underline[/b], [b]overline[/b], or [b]line-through[/b] values in a space-separated list to add multiple decoration lines.[/note]

